y sphere which shapes the field of action for the individual at every turn. This, unsurprisingly, does not appeal to rights-holders themselves.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCritical theory. 0aHuman rightsxPolitical aspects. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Human Rights.2bisacsh  aMichael Oakeshott.  aMichel Foucault.  afreedom.  aglobal governance.  agovernmentality.  ahuman rights.  ainternational law.  amanagerialism.  apastoral power.  athe state.1 aMcGrogan, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packagez978311128198840uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152613183640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526131836423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526131836/original  a978-3-11-128198-8  Manchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packageb2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles